PHS Girls Cross Country
Today at 1:19 AM ·

The PHS Girls Cross Country teams came home with a 2nd place finish at the Hallsville Invitational last Week!
The Ladycats were led by Emerith Hernandez who finished in 3rd place, followed by Emily Marroquín 6th, Macy French in 15th , Yaneli Ruiz in 17th, and Brenda Treviño 18th place!

Jv girls were led by Alliyah Estrada 6th, Celeste Lara 7th, Samantha Chaidez 8th and Amy Rangel 9th place.

The teams will be back in action next Thursday September 17th @ the Mineola invitational!!!

JH girls finished 6th place overall. They were led by Carla Aleman, Ana Ibarra, Hope Garcia, Rebecca Campa, and Ellie Benítez.

The JH girls will be back in action next Saturday September 19th @ Mineola!

Thank you so much for your support!!

Go ladycats!! #beatHudson

shared_text:
Palestine Wildcats Soccer
September 15 at 2:40 PM ·

Palestine Cross Country had a busy week on all levels.
Wednesday, one of the JV squads and JH competed in Latexo. The JV finished second to Crockett in the varsity race. Top five were Oben Reyes (3rd), Ricoh Avila, Andy Garcia, Kristian Olvera and Ty Anders. The JH took first in their race being paced by Kevin Quincin (1st), Joseph Fabian (2nd), Manny Campa (5th), Juan Lopez (10th) and Sebastian Ledesma-Hernandez.
Thursday started the Hallsville meets. JV was first up with a first place finish in their heat. Top runners were Esvin Quincin (4th), Cruz Villanueva (5th), Tony Garcia (6th), Diego Farias (7th) and David Arredondo (8th). Friday was varsity’s turn to run, they finished second in their heat to Kilgore. They were led by Luis Rangel (3rd), Jalbert Sandoval (4th), Michael Chaidez (6th), Luis Castillo (10th) and Gabriel Gante. Saturday morning rounded out the week with JH taking first place in their heat. Kevin Quincin (1st), Joseph Fabian (4th), Manny Campa (5th), Juan Lopez (7th) and Ivan Ruiz (10th) led the team to the win.

post_text: Congratulations ladies!!!!
shared_text:
J'Ann Sartain is with Aven Alexander and 5 others.
September 10 at 9:47 PM ·

The U.S. Congress will confer it's highest youth award, the Congressional Gold Medal, to these three outstanding young ladies in a virtual ceremony on September 26, 2020. In the more than 30 year history of the Congressional Award there have only been five earned by young adults in the Texas 5th Congressional District: Haleigh (2020), Nat (2020), Aven (2020), and Briana Minter (2017), and Monica Attaway (2018) -- All from Anderson County!! These three won't get to go to the Capitol to collect their medals, but their achievements mark them forever as spectacular ladies. We are so proud of you!!! Ship1, Unique

#thecongressionalaward

The week of November 16-21st will be used for games missed due to bad weather. Registration is $30.00 per student and will be turned it to your child's PE teacher. Please contact Nancy Malone at 979.446.6470 with questions or if you would like to coach or volunteer.

shared_text:
UT TYLER Palestine Campus
September 1 at 1:55 PM ·

Next up in our meet the faculty series is Gina Dudley, MSN, RN.

I started my nursing career more than 26 years ago as a LVN, later acquiring my Associate Degree in Nursing. While working in the hospital setting, I had the pleasure of being mentored by many wonderful nurses that inspired me to pursue higher education. In 2014, I graduated from University of Phoenix with my Masters of Science Degree in Nursing.
I have worked in a variety of settings ranging from Medical - Surgical , Intensive Care, Pediatrics and Community Health. As a eager life learner, pouring into others has always been my passion. I am truly blessed that The University of Texas at Tyler has allowed me the opportunity to help others discover their purpose and passion and fulfill their dreams. The moment your student has a WOW factor is such a wonderful feeling. It gives me pleasure to see our past students successfully working within our profession to improve health care not only in our community, but all over the world.

Due to Covid restrictions Palestine Varsity Football tickets will now be sold online only. There will be no tickets sold at the gate. Tickets will remain available to purchase up through game time until they are all sold.
Kick off is Friday, September 4 at Wildcat Stadium. The link to purchase tickets will open at noon Tuesday, September 1.

Link to purchase:
https://schooleventticketslogin.com/event/view/wildcats-vs-lions2

All tickets will be $6.25 each. No one will be allowed admission without a ticket. Please bring a printed copy of your ticket or have a copy on your phone to present to the staff at the gate. Passes are not accepted due to Covid-19 restrictions.

post_text: What a morning in the Wildcat Nation celebrating the Texas Teacher Incentive Allotment award winners. A BIG THANK YOU to PHS CHEER and PHS DRUMLINE for helping us celebrate in style. Palestine ISD was honored to be accepted as one of 24 districts in the great state of TEXAS in COHORT A. This allotment awards district state funds to pay bonuses to teachers based on their evaluations and student improvement. The state range of awards is from $3000.00 to $32,000.00 each year for five years. Teachers my be awarded the status of recognized, exemplary or master teacher. The Wildcat Nation had ten teachers awarded bonuses for a grand total award of $341,055.00. This is such a wonderful achievement for the teachers as well as a boost to the local economy. Teachers receiving distinctions are: PHS-Mrs. Armstrong and Mrs. Magee, PJH- Mrs. Reeves, Mrs.Templin, Mrs. Vaughn, A. M. Story-Mrs. Bowden, Mr. Lazarine, Mr Odom, Ms. Reagan, and Mrs. Thigpen. The Wildcat Nation is proud of you.

post_text:
Palestine ISD is committed to keeping all students and staff safe and healthy and communicating to families any situations relating to COVID on campuses. This is message is to notify everyone that although, there have been no lab confirmed cases at this time, some students on the Washington ECC and Southside Elementary campuses have exhibited symptoms. These students as well as those who may have had close contact have been sent home.
Palestine ISD will follow the established COVID sanitizing protocol for disinfecting the classrooms and other areas. Additionally, we ask everyone to be mindful of the symptoms related to COVID: headache, fever exceeding 100 degrees, cough not associated with any other health issues, vomiting, and diarrhea. Please contact your campus principal immediately if any symptoms appear.

post_text: The Wildcat Nation is beyond proud of staff, students, parents and community who have stepped up to make remote learning a tool for these challenging times. Here is a quick tip for communicating with your teachers. Students may use the Inbox on Canvas to contact their teachers in any course on Canvas..Click the Inbox on the left side of screen and then select the pencil edit tool, select from the drop down menus, write a message and send. There is so much to learn but together we have this conquered!!!!

post_text: There is something new at A.M. Story for afternoon dismissal to make sure students, staff and community remain safe and healthy. Parents will have two options for student pickup at the end of the day. Students may be bus riders or car riders. All car riders will dismiss from the grade level ramps. The big change is A.M. Story will no longer have walkers or walk up student pick ups at the car ramp area or in the front foyer. Due to health and safety concerns A. M. Story and all campuses are limiting building access and groups gathering. Please, also remember students who need to leave early must be checked out 30 minutes prior to the end of the school day. Any emergency check outs may be done by calling the A. M. Story office. Also due to Covid restrictions, outside food deliveries will not be permitted.

The Pride of Palestine: The Fighting Wildcat Band is sharing a COVID-19 Update.
July 9 at 5:35 PM ·

Hey Band! We are restarting High School Summer Band activities with administration permission on Monday July 13th with Percussion. Attached is the revised summer band schedule for the month of July with more specific COVID-19 mitigation procedures.

The Band Boosters will be providing a Palestine Wildcat Band Neck Gaiter so that everyone will be uniform, and have a face covering that is easy to use when in rehearsal and performances (if face coverings are still required when we start performances) These will be free to all marching band members. Thank you very much to our amazing Band Boosters!!

Until our uniform face coverings arrive, everyone will need to provide their own face covering for rehearsals.

Please review this information carefully! If you have questions, please feel free to message us here, or call/text Mr. Alonso at 903-345-4741.

post_text: Se ha ampliado el plazo para solicitar los beneficios alimentarios de la Transferencia Electrónica de Beneficios por Pandemia (P-EBT, por sus siglas en inglés) hasta el 31 de julio. ¿Recibió su hijo comidas escolares gratuitas o a precio reducido a través del Programa Nacional de Almuerzos Escolares (National School Lunch Program) durante el año escolar 2019-2020? Si es así, su familia puede ser elegible para este beneficio alimentario único. Visite hhs.texas.gov/pebt para obtener más información sobre la P-EBT. Si tiene preguntas relacionadas con la elegibilidad o si necesita ayuda para presentar la solicitud, comuníquese con el Centro de Atención al Cliente de la P-EBT al 833-613-6220. La regla de carga pública no se aplica a los beneficios de la P-EBT.

This data will be compiled to create an up-to-date broadband map and analysis for Anderson County to show us areas we struggle with connection to the internet at a reliable speed. We still need more than 200 homeowners or lease tenants to complete this survey data. If you are frustrated with your internet connection speeds, please take 5 - 10 minutes to complete this brief survey to help our leaders assess future needs for our community.

https://www.myconnectedcommunity.org/anderson-county/

post_text:
SENIOR 2020 SPOTLIGHT: Noah Alexander
is an exceptional student!
During his high school years he has dedicated his time and talents to Theatre, UIL One Act Play, UIL Academics, Top Ten, National Honor Society, Rotary Academic Olympics, Fellowship of Christian Athletes, Chemistry Club, Palestine Chamber of Commerce Junior Ambassador, SAT/Math Tutor, Chem/APES Lab Assistant, Chess Club, Carter Blood Care Donor and served as a Kick-Kat Captain Escort and Baseball Manager. Noah won the Leaders of Tomorrow Award from TVCC as a junior in 2019 and earned a spot on the Presidential List. He will be graduating with an Associates Degree from TVCC in addition to his PHS Diploma.
Noah was awarded the prestigious Tier One Scholarship by the University of Houston Honors College! He was 1 of 14 students selected to receive this award, making him the first student in the history of #WildcatNation to earn this scholarship!
Noah will be pursuing an honors degree in Software Engineering starting in the fall. WE ARE VERY PROUD OF YOUR DEDICATION NOAH!
#palestinetx #PHSClassof2020 #UHHonorsCollege

Congratulations seniors 2020! Anahi Hernandez (#2) has been a member of the Ladycat Soccer and Cross Country teams for 4 years. After Graduation, she plans to attend Tyler Junior College and work on becoming an Occupational Therapist Assistant.
Her proudest accomplishment as a ladycat soccer player was: “making it to the third round of playoffs last year”
Her most memorable moment as part of the ladycat soccer team was: “making my first goal on varsity last year and going to the Forney Tournament”
What she will miss the most about being a ladycat are: “Bus rides with all my teammates and especially the free food”

post_text: Taylor Kelly a member of the National Honor Society, the National Speech and Debate Honor Society, the current issues and events team, the UIL Student Congress, Lincoln Douglas debate, and extemporaneous speaking team, the legislative Youth and Government team, the Academic Olympics team, and the National History Academy. She is president of Youth and Government, where she won awards at the state competition three years in a row. She is also president of the Speech and Debate club and is the class historian for the National Honor Society. She is a member of Wildcat University and will be graduating with her associate’s degree from TVCC in May. She plans to attend Ole Miss in the fall to pursue a degree in Public Policy Leadership with the hope of becoming a lawyer or a campaign manager.

Good evening to everyone.
This is Jason Marshall, Palestine ISD Superintendent.
As I’m sure you know by now, Governor Abbott has closed on-campus learning for all schools for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year.
Therefore, Palestine ISD will continue providing meals and Home Learning Packets to students as we have for the last month.

Please visit our PISD web page or our PISD Facebook page for my latest letter addressing the Covid-19 situation and our continued response.
Have a nice evening.

In honor of the graduating Class of 2020, we honor soon-to-be graduate Allyson Byrd. She is a 6 year member of the PISD choir. She is also a 6 year member of the Region 21 All-Region Choir (JH and HS, including both Honor Choir and Small School Choir). Allyson attended 4 years of the Texas State Solo&Ensemble contest in Austin where she earned a number of gold and silver medals.

She will attend Sam Houston State University in the fall of 2020, where she plans to major in elementary education. In fact, she looks forward to “going to college and learning how to become a successful teacher.”

Allyson plans to teach 3rd grade.

We love you, Ally and will miss all your “WA” moments!! 💖💖💖

CDC
April 6 at 7:59 PM ·

Use a cloth face covering in public to reduce the spread of COVID-19.
Your cloth face covering should:

✔️Reach above the nose, below the chin, and completely cover the mouth and nostrils
✔️Fit snugly against the sides of the face
✔️Be made of multiple layers of fabric that you can still breathe through
✔️Be able to be laundered and machine dried without damaging the material or shape

Do not buy surgical masks to use as a face covering. Those are intended for healthcare workers and first responders. Many items you may already have in your home can be used to create face coverings. Try creating a cloth face covering using bandanas, ski masks, washable napkins, or dish towels. https://bit.ly/2Ravt42

March 19 at 10:04 PM ·

The Hospice of East Texas is excited about our Happy Mail project!

Happy Mail is designed to combat loneliness and brighten the days of area seniors while encouraging our community to remember those most at risk during this national health crisis. We are encouraging people of all ages to write notes, create artwork and color pictures for delivery to residents of local nursing and assisted living facilities. We have a system in place so Happy Mail can be delivered safely to these individuals.

Happy Mail can be sent to:
Happy Mail
c/o The Hospice of East Texas
4111 University Blvd
Tyler, TX 75701

OR

Just message me through Facebook or call or text me at (409) 656-8799 for more information or to participate!

More details: http://spr.ly/61861subu.

shared_text:
Palestine Wildcats Soccer
March 7 at 1:58 AM ·

Tonight we honor Coach John Absalom on his 600th career coaching win. With this win he joins three other coaches with 600 or more wins on the Texas Association of Soccer Coaches list and is the 15th coach all-time to reach this mark nationally according to the National Federation of High Schools website. Coach Absalom has accumulated these wins across 4 schools, Killeen, Whitehouse, Jacksonville and Palestine. Coach Absalom has accumulated 354 of those wins here at Palestine, with 314 on the boys side and 40 on the girls. Among those wins were four trips to the state tournament and one state championship in boys soccer. In addition he has also won three regional titles and had numerous state meet appearances in boys and girls cross country. Your family, friends, fellow coaches and players thank you for all your tireless dedication, preparation and discipline that have gotten these programs to these elite levels. We are proud of you and on to 700!

post_text:
Each year 79,000 teenagers are victims of sex trafficking in Texas.

Refuge of Light is a non-profit organization whose mission is to provide a safe haven, redemptive rescue and restoration of female victims of domestic minor sex trafficking.

We are going to do our part to help Refuge of Light, and here’s how you can do your part too.

Come join us at Davey Dogwood Park for the 3rd annual Refuge Run and Doggie Dash. It’s going to be an exciting 5k run that you can do with or without your favorite k9 pal. We’re going to have a blast starting at 7:30am Saturday, March 21st.You can register online with Refuge of Light.org or you can sign up the morning of.

So put your running shoes on, grab your pup and a leash, and take a stand against sex trafficking with Refuge of Light.

Palestine Ladycat Athletics
February 25 at 3:51 PM ·

Last night the Ladycats hosted Brownsboro in their final game of the season. All the ladies stepped up and played their best game of the year. Christell Francia opened the night with an unassisted goal racing past the defense and finding the back of the net twice for the night. Her second goal was assisted by Valeria Garcia. Helena Lara scored on a corner kick assisted by Andrea Molina and another goal assisted by Vanessa Diaz. Citkali Desantiago added the dagger to seal the game on a loan goal dribbling through traffic. The final score of the night was 5-1.

post_text:
The Palestine High School and Palestine Junior High Robotics Teams both competed in the South Texas Championship this weekend in Houston. They celebrated before competing this weekend for qualifying for the Regional Tournament.

PHS took home the Build Award for an exceptional and innovative design. Palestine Junior High went undefeated 12 matches in, until the tournament final where they just fell short of wining the entire tournament. They came home with the Tournament Finalists trophy.

This was an exceptional finish to the Palestine Junior High season, and they are extremely excited for the damage they can do next year at the high school level. Palestine High School will compete at the State Tournament in March.

shared_text:
Palestine Wildcats Soccer
January 29 at 3:22 PM ·

Varsity: Palestine 4, Lindale 0

The 4A State Ranked #1 Wildcats (16-1-0) opened up their week of 5A opponents with a win over the Eagles, 4-0. The ‘Cats scored all four goals in a seven minute span in the second half. JJ Garcia got the scoring started when he took a pass from Diego Farias and shot from distance. Luis Rangel was next up with a goal off a Garcia assist. Jose Sanchez scored the third with an assist from Lizardo Lemus. Tony Garcia finished off the scoring with the assist from Rangel. Christian Hutchinson rounded up another clean sheet with help from Jhan Vazquez, Brian Armenta, Yoriel Reyes, Lemus, Alex Garcia, Ian Oliva, Esiel Vigil and Michael Guzman. The Wildcats have not given up a goal in the last 464 minutes of game time.

Picture: Gary Munoz (2) settles the ball against Lindale.

post_text:
The Ladycats JV and V Basketball teams failed to capture their first district win tonight against Fairfield.

JV GIRLS
JV girls had a close game and lead with 1:35 to play but poor free throw shooting down the stretch hurt the team and lead to the loss.

VARSITY GIRLS
The varsity girls basketball team started the game with great defensive intensity and focus and trailed by 4 at the end of the 1st quarter. However, a low scoring second quarter, too many turnovers and lack of rebounding lead to the Ladycats taking a loss Fairfield.

Both teams will play at home on Friday the 17th vs. Mexia. JV will start at 5 pm and Varsity will follow.

VARSITY GIRLS
The varsity girls basketball team started the game with great defensive intensity and focus and trailed by 4 at the end of the 1st quarter. However, a low scoring second quarter, too many turnovers and lack of rebounding lead to the Ladycats taking a loss Fairfield.

Both teams will play at home on Friday the 17th vs. Mexia. JV will start at 5 pm and Varsity will follow.
